            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Thomas Lin\u2019s life began in the quiet, sun-drenched suburbs of Fremont, a world away from the fog-laced city he now calls home. The only child of a pragmatic software engineer and a homemaker with a passion for gardening, Thomas grew up navigating two distinct value systems. His father championed logic and a stable career path, while his mother taught him the names of birds and the quiet satisfaction of tending to the earth, her garden a vibrant oasis of loquats and jasmine.\n\nHis true calling was ignited not in a classroom, but during a family trip. At ten, he stood in awe of the granite majesty of Yosemite. Four years later, they returned to a different section of the park, finding a familiar landscape scarred and blackened by wildfire. The stark contrast between memory and reality imprinted on him a profound sense of urgency, a feeling that the natural world he cherished was fragile and in need of defenders. This conviction guided him to UC Davis, where he pursued a Bachelor's degree in Urban Studies, focusing on sustainable development and environmental policy.\n\nNow 26, Thomas works as an environmental consultant from his apartment in the Inner Richmond. With a commute of zero miles, his days are a disciplined blend of digital meetings, data analysis, and writing reports on environmental impact and green building standards. His mornings don't start on a crowded MUNI bus but with a run through Golden Gate Park, the fog dampening the scent of eucalyptus. His work, while intellectually stimulating, often feels abstract\u2014a series of recommendations on a screen.\n\nTo bridge the gap between policy and practice, Thomas spends his weekends volunteering with habitat restoration projects in the Marin Headlands, his hands in the very soil he advocates for protecting. He maintains a close-knit circle of college friends, often meeting for dim sum on Clement Street or hiking trails on Mount Tamalpais. His quiet ambition isn't for a corner office, but to one day lead a tangible project, like daylighting one of San Francisco's buried creeks. He dreams of rewriting the city's relationship with its natural landscape, ensuring that future generations have their own pristine places to stand in awe of."
